serinfo.issue: Queensland geological mapping (polygonised vector) Digital Data - July 2012 DVD

descript.abstract: The polygons in this dataset are a digital representation of the distribution or extent of geological units within Queensland. Polygons have a range of attributes including unit name, type of unit, age, lithological description, dominant rock type, and an abbreviated symbol for use in labelling the polygons. These have been extracted from the Rock Units Table held in the Department of Natural Resources and Mines MERLIN Database.
descript.purpose: To display the geology polygons which define the extent of rock units.
descript.supplinf: Digital Data was generalised and simplified from the Department's detailed geological data and was captured at 1:500 000 scale for output at 1:2 000 000 scale. The data set is sourced from the Department's Geoscience and Resources Database (GRDB), a component of the Mineral and Energy Resources Location and Information Network (MERLIN) corporate database.

attrdomv.udom: Sequential unique whole numbers that are automatically generated.

attr.attrdef: Unique polygon identifier and relate item for surface geology polygon attributes
Provides a brief description of the rock types forming the map units as they have been described in the course of the project work, or as has appeared on relevant hard copy map legends

Provides an abbreviated label for polygons. Mostly based on the letter symbols as they appear on published maps or the original hard copy compilation sheets. These are not unique across the State, but should be unique within each original source dataset migrated to the geodatabase
A simplified lithological description to allow generation of thematic maps based on broad rock types
Provides a means of separating map units, eg for constructing a map reference.

The Map Unit Name of the polygon. In the case of single, named units it comprises the standard binomial name. This map also contains composite units which may be a list of binomially named units and/or informal descriptive names. Some unnamed Cenozoic units are represented by a letter symbol, in combination with the suffix QLD, indicating that they are Queensland-wide units.

Provides a means of separating map units, eg for constructing a map reference. This item will contain one of the following: STRATIFIED UNIT (INCLUDING VOLCANIC AND METAMORPHIC), INTRUSIVE and COMPOSITE UNIT (SOMINANTLY STRATIFIED)
A unique color code created from the Red, Green, Blue colour percentages used in the polygon layer colouring. The formula is (red * 65536) + (green * 256) + blue
attr.attrdefs: The R,G,B values for standard geological map colours as assigned to the dataset using a combination of the Age, Rock Unit Type and Rock Unit Name fields

overview.dsoverv: Geoldata- Polygonised vector data, is a spatial representation of geological mapping with attached attributes. This polygon feature data consists of two parts, the spatial information and the attribute information. Spatial information includes geology polygons which define the extent of rock units within the study area.
overview.eaover: Polygon Attribute information includes Key, Name, Map Symbol, Lith Summ, Age Name, Dom Rock, and Unit Type.

attracc.attraccr: Geological units (and their boundaries) were derived by simplifiication of previous more detailed mapping. This previous mapping was carried in conjunction with interpretation of aerial photographs by numerous field observations and or measurements, and sample collection and analysis.

dataqual.complete: Completeness and consistency of classification needs to be considered in the context of the time span of the source mapping and the highly interpretive nature of the discipline. Although broadly similar classification and measurement techniques have been applied to geological map compilation by geological surveys for many years, resultant data tends to reflect individual geologists' ideas and preferences. For example the classification of boundaries, faults and similar features (ranging from approximate, concealed, inferred) is not particularly consistent and needs to be treated with caution. There is no consistent record of the extent of field observation as opposed to air-photo interpretation, but location of sites in the Geological Site Database available from the Department of Natural Resources and Mines (and extracted from its MERLIN corporate database) gives an indication of the level of fieldwork undertaken for mapping carried out since 1986.

horizpa.horizpar: An accurate assessment of the horizontal accuracy is not possible. This dataset was digitised from hardcopy compilation sheets at 1:500 000 that were generalised by manually tracing from reductions of more detailed maps originally at a scale of 1:100 000 or 1:250000 with the purpose of producing lines and polygons that could be readable at an output scale of 1:2 000 000. It is estimated that at best the positional accuracy in the original maps could be of the order of 200m for the 1:250 000 maps and 50m for the 1:100 000 maps. The tracing, generalisation and digitising would have introduced further errors and at 1:500 000 scale, assuming a 1mm tolerance in positioning a line, these would be 500m or more. It is stressed that this does not take into account the uncertainties in original interpretation and location of these features, so that the actual error may be much greater.
